        "body": "`\nSELECT\n        row_to_json(fc)  \n    FROM\n        ( SELECT\n            'FeatureCollection' As type,\n            array_to_json(array_agg(f)) As features  \n        FROM\n            (SELECT\n                'Feature' As type ,\n                ST_AsGeoJSON(ST_ConcaveHull(ST_Collect(ST_Transform(lg.geom, 4326)), 0.99))::json As geometry,\n                row_to_json((SELECT l FROM (SELECT code_posta) As l )) As properties    \n      \t     FROM addresses As lg\n             WHERE code_posta IS NOT NULL\n             GROUP by code_posta\n            ) As f )  As fc;\n`",

    {
      "content": {
        "body": "I also used spatialite before, but since QGIS 3.xx i switched entirely to the new format. Geopackage seems to be superior to spatialite (both are SQLite based) - as it is a geographic standard from the OGC (while spatialite is just a spatial format among others). It is designed to replace shapefile a the defacto standard when doing spatial analysis... It's new but modern and get all the bonus from spatialite + some others things. And if you use QGIS, you'll find that the processing speed is multiple times faster when using geopackage than any other format (as it is optimised for it) - and you can directly save into the existing database when outputing results. So it makes data processing easier than ever - and also exchanging the dataset as it is one file (like spatialite). ",
        "msgtype": "m.text"
      },

    {
      "content": {
        "body": "I get that for 1 device it's the way to go.  I'm dealing with thousands of GPS trackers, which , if they all generated data like that, it's a lot of data to store, and this is in a database, not a file.  And most of it is useless.  vehicles stand still more time than they move.  The event based approach is quite advanced though.   Corners are fine, if you select the right angles,  I also have G-sensors, and start/stops, speed events,   And all sorts of combinations, like below 30km/h : take a sample every 5 meters, above: take a sample every 500meter (highways) etc.  But I agree if for personal use, you like to get as much as you can.  The only problem sometimes with that aproach is that GPS fixes might fail and/or be of lower quality, which makes your route (if all samples would be displayed on a map) make funny jumps.   That's something customers really don't like, although it can be explained.   Also, it's aheadache to filter out timers when a vehicle stands still, since none of the points are on the same spot due to the inaccuracy in the GPS data (deliberately).",

        "body": "More accurate GPS would help in two ways : 3/ better accuracy when geotagging photos for Mapillary and 4/ track that's more in line with reality when improving for example winding forest paths. \n\nGalileo is the buzzword, understand there are two signals : the GPS L1 / Galileo E1 - which promise in the order of 3 to 5 m accuracy (but deliver errors up to 30m), and Galileo E5a which some sources promise will be better than 1m, others promise 30cm accuracy - take that with a pinch of salt, would still be a huge improvement over the current unit's 'guestimate'. \n",

    {
      "content": {
        "body": "No, not really.\nStandard used has nothing to do with the speed. :)\n\nTMS is similar to XYZ (the way OSM tiles are served) : each tile has a coordinate (X, Y, Zoom Level) and an url point to each individual tile (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tiled_web_map)\n\nWMTS is \"between\" TMS/XYZ and WMS.\nYou can request the WMTS service to give you the list of layers available, query the objects, ... (all of those are not provided by TMS/XYZ) (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_Map_Tile_Service).",

        "body": "I've been thinking about the Urbis version problem.
